\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 7 Problem Two
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
2.
 A Bundt cake, well known for having a ringed shape, is formed by revolving
 around the y-axis the region bounded by the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=sin(x^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

 and around the x-axis over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq x\leq\sqrt{1+\pi}.$
\end_inset

 Find the volume of the cake.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As shown by the graph provided on the problem sheet, the most practical
 way to find the volume of a bundt cake would be to use the shell method
 for the solid of revolution created by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $y=sin(x^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq x\leq\sqrt{1+\pi}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula for shell method is given by the following: 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\int2\pi rhdx$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the radius and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the height of the cylindrical shells that are formed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

in this case is the distance measured in x from the y-axis, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 to the function, so thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $r=x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in this case is the distance between the x-axis and the height of the function,
 which is just 
\begin_inset Formula $y=sin(x^{2}-1)=h$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the volume is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V=\int_{1}^{\sqrt{1+\pi}}2\pi xsin(x^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
